	doi = {10.1109/ICI3C60830.2023.00019},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/85209894025?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {The goal of this project is to explore the topic of software defect prediction and provide a novel method for enhancing prediction model performance by fusing hybrid crowd intelligence with deep learning. In the study, we first use deep learning autoencoder for data dimensionality reduction, and achieve supervised pre-training of high-dimensional data by learning the intrinsic features of the data. Then, a deep neural network-based software defect prediction model was constructed, in which a hybrid population intelligence algorithm was used for hyperparameter optimisation. The hybrid algorithm combines the advantages of particle swarm optimisation and wolf pack algorithms for better global exploration and local optimisation when searching the hyperparameter space. In our experiments, we used a software defect dataset containing 58 features and compared the performance of five hyperparameter optimisation methods such as grid algorithm, stochastic algorithm, particle swarm algorithm, wolf pack algorithm and hybrid wolf pack algorithm. The experimental results show that the model using the hybrid wolfpack algorithm exhibits significant advantages in four evaluation metrics, including precision, recall, F-measure and AUC, and achieves more robust software defect prediction compared to other methods. This study not only promotes the application of deep learning in the field of software engineering, but also provides new empirical support for the effectiveness of group intelligence algorithms in software defect prediction.  © 2023 IEEE.},
