	abstract = {The study introduces Newton's Downhill Optimizer (NDO), a novel metaheuristic algorithm designed to tackle complex, high-dimensional, and nonlinear optimization problems. Optimization is crucial in various fields such as engineering and medical diagnostics. However, existing algorithms often struggle with the nonlinearity and multimodal nature of real-world problems. NDO integrates the precision of Newton's method with a downhill strategy inspired by stochastic processes. It enhances the exploration of the solution space and avoids local optima by introducing the SSO and the HGO to effectively guide the population search process. It is particularly effective in addressing real-world applications and benchmark problems. NDO was tested against 14 established optimization algorithms, including mathematical-based algorithms (AOA, SCHO, SCA, SABO, NRBO, and RUN), classical methods (CMA-ES, ABC, DE, PSO), and advanced algorithms (WSO, EHO, FDB_AGDE, GQPSO). The results showed that NDO outperforms most of these algorithms in terms of convergence speed and stability. In engineering applications, NDO excelled in tasks such as speed reducer design, step-cone pulley tasks, and disk clutch brake design. A key contribution of this study is applying NDO to breast cancer feature selection using two datasets. NDO demonstrated exceptional performance, achieving high accuracy (ACC), sensitivity (SEN), specificity (SPE), and Matthews Correlation Coefficient (MCC). This highlights NDO's potential as an effective tool for solving complex problems in both engineering and medical fields. This study highlights NDO's potential as an effective tool for solving complex optimization problems in both engineering and medical fields. The source code for the NDO is available at https://github.com/oykc1234/NDO. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd},
