	abstract = {As mineral resource development moves deeper, the stability of rock masses under high ground pressure, high stress, and complex geological environments becomes increasingly prominent. Effectively monitoring rock mass conditions and identifying potential instability risks has become a core issue in deep mining research. Microseismic monitoring technology, as an important means of disaster identification and early warning, can provide crucial information on rock mass mechanical behavior, offering technical support for preventing rock mass instability disasters. This paper, based on the microseismic monitoring system of the Woxi Gold-Antimony-Tungsten Mine of Chenzhou Mining in Hunan Province, conducts research on microseismic parameter prediction for rock mass instability disasters based on time-series models. First, 14 sets of typical source parameters were collected. Data feature engineering and principal component analysis (PCA) were used to systematically preprocess and reduce the dimensionality of the raw data. Then, four typical time-series models were selected, and the time series of parameters were used to dynamically predict microseismic energy. Finally, to further improve prediction accuracy and model robustness, a particle swarm optimization (PSO) algorithm was introduced to globally optimize the model hyperparameters, confirming that complex structural models can achieve ideal results in high-dimensional parameter spaces through reasonable parameter tuning. Finally, a comprehensive evaluation of the model's iterative convergence process and prediction error distribution revealed that GRU and Attention performed best in terms of convergence speed and prediction stability. The research results show that the microseismic parameter prediction method based on deep learning models has good feasibility and practicality in improving the accuracy of rock mass instability prediction, and can provide new ideas for intelligent perception and proactive prevention and control of deep mine disasters. Copyright © 2024. Published by Elsevier B.V.},
