	abstract = {Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAVs) have evolved from various domains such as environmental monitoring, infrastructure inspection, and search and rescue by enabling rapid, flexible, and cost effective data collection. This study presents a comprehensive comparative study of two meta heuristic optimization algorithms for path planning in complex obstacle rich environments. This study implements and evaluates the Hybrid Chaotic Pattern Search Algorithm (HCPSA) with five different chaotic maps (Chebyshev, Cubic, ICMIC, Neuron, and Sine) against Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO) for multi objective path optimization. The study utilizes a real world UAV dataset containing GPS coordinates, IMU sensor data, and environmental parameters. This unique methodology incorporates comprehensive data preprocessing, feature engineering, and multi criteria optimization considering path length, safety constraints, energy consumption, and trajectory smoothness. Experimental results demonstrate that while HCPSA with Neuron chaotic map achieves the best safety focused solution (fitness: 1582.63), PSO consistently outperforms HCPSA variants by providing better balanced solutions between efficiency and safety. The Neuron map showed superior performance among chaotic variants, achieving 46% better fitness compared to the badly performing ICMIC map. PSO's population based search strategy and velocity-driven exploration prove more effective than HCPSA's single point pattern search approach for the high dimensional UAV path planning problem. These findings provide valuable insights for autonomous UAV navigation system design and meta heuristic algorithm selection in aerospace applications. © 2025 IEEE.},
	type = {Conference paper},
	publication_stage = {Final},
	source = {Scopus},
	note = {Cited by: 0}
