	abstract = {These days, there has been enormous progress in technologies for predicting high-dimensional data. More specifically, semantic segmentation for pictures including various objects, or pixel-level prediction for physical values like depth and normal direction are representative examples of them. Notably, the Unet, which is a neural network consisting of consecutive layers of convolution and deconvolution layer, is widely used for this purpose. Meanwhile, numerical simulation is the most time-consuming step of contemporary optimal design for hull form. To avoid the bottleneck caused by simulation, most of the simulation-based design processes include surrogate models. For example, the kriging model or neural network-based model has been utilized to predict a few numbers of performance metrics such as wave resistance coefficient. In this study, however, the Unet-based surrogate model was proposed to predict the high-dimensional performance metric; the pressure distribution on the hull surface. To obtain the training dataset, hull form modification and potential flow analysis were conducted. The surrogate model was then combined with another neural network for hull generation to form an objective function neural network. The particle swarm optimization algorithm was employed to get an optimal hull form in an explainable way. It was found that the modified hull form was correlated with the predicted pressure distribution in a physically meaningful way, thereby proving the effectiveness of the present method in realizing an AI-based hull form optimization technique. © 2024 by the International Society of Offshore and Polar Engineers (ISOPE).},
