	doi = {10.13637/j.issn.1009-6094.2025.0446},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105030063629?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {To address the issue of low accuracy in traditional fault diagnosis methods for coded track circuits, this paper proposes a novel fault diagnosis approach that integrates feature selection with the Dung Beetle Optimizer (DBO) algorithm to optimize the Deep Extreme Learning Machine (DELM) . First, the ReliefF algorithm is employed to preprocess the dataset for feature selection. By comparing the similarities and differences between samples, effective data features are identified, and the importance of each feature for classification is evaluated and quantified. Features deemed highly important are selected, thereby mitigating the influence of redundant data on diagnostic accuracy. The data following feature selection serves as the input dataset for the DELM model. Next, the diagnostic accuracy of DELM is utilized as the basis for updating the parameters of DBO. Through iterative optimization, the process gradually converges to the optimal solution, resulting in the identification of optimal weights. This approach addresses the issue of random initial weight settings in DELM. Ultimately, the optimal weights obtained from DBO are used as the initial weights for the DELM model to diagnose 12 types of faults in coded track circuits. The 12 coded encoding faults are divided into two datasets, E<sub>1</sub> and E<sub>2</sub> , for fault diagnosis. The diagnostic accuracy of these two datasets is compared to assess the robustness of the model. The improved DELM algorithm achieved diagnostic accuracy rates of 98. 57% and 99% on the two datasets, respectively, demonstrating strong classification performance across both datasets. To further validate the effectiveness of the proposed method, DBO is compared with Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO) and Grey Wolf Optimizer (GWO) . The findings indicate that the improved method demonstrates superior convergence speed and generalization ability. It shows significant enhancements across multiple metrics, including diagnostic accuracy, recall rate, and F<sub>1</sub> score, compared to other classification models. The results suggest that through data preprocessing via ReliefF and optimization of DELM using DBO, fault diagnosis accuracy is not only improved but also remains unaffected by high-dimensional data, showcasing excellent robustness. This highlights the method’s feasibility in the field of track circuit fault diagnosis. © 2026 Editorial Department of Journal of Safety and Environment. All rights reserved.},
