	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105036543481?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Precision agriculture aims to optimize crop yield and resource utilization through data-driven insights. However, high-dimensional datasets often hinder accurate predictions due to improper feature selection, leading to overfitting, reduced precision and recall rates, and an increased false positive rate. This essay offers a fresh method for address these challenges in the context of agricultural supply chain and production data augmented with seasonal scores. The method begins with Z-score normalization to pre-process the dataset, ensuring consistent scaling across features. Subsequently, Seasonal Support Impact Rate (SSIR) and On-Demand Supply Chain Impact Rate (ODSCIR) are estimated using a Decisive Vector Tree, providing a quantitative measure of feature importance based on seasonal and demand factors. To mitigate the curse of dimensionality, a Spider Swarm Particle Swarm Optimization (SSPSO) algorithm is employed for efficient feature selection, prioritizing features with high seasonal support. Finally, a Deep Scaled Convnet Hyper Capsuled GAN network (DSCHS-GAN) is leveraged to forecast product demand, providing farmers with cultivation recommendations designed to maximize yield. Experimental results show that, in comparison to conventional methods, the suggested system greatly enhances prediction performance, attaining greater precision, recall, F1-measure, and total detection accuracy. © 2025 IEEE.},
