	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105018605463?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {As the global manufacturing industry transitions towards intelligence and sustainability, mechanical manufacturing enterprises face multiple challenges in improving production efficiency, reducing energy consumption, and optimizing resource allocation. In the field of mechanical manufacturing, traditional production optimization methods are often inefficient and struggle to adapt to complex and dynamic production demands. This study proposes a novel mechanical manufacturing production optimization method based on a neighborhood search-improved particle swarm optimization algorithm to address these limitations. A multi-objective optimization model is constructed, incorporating critical factors such as production time, energy consumption, equipment idle time, and cost. The algorithm's local optimization capability is enhanced by dynamically adjusting the search radius. This effectively overcomes the tendency of conventional particle swarm optimization algorithms to prematurely converge or settle into local optima in high-dimensional, multimodal scenarios. The performance of the proposed method was validated through experiments conducted under both small-scale and large-scale production scenarios. Compared to traditional methods, the proposed algorithm achieved significant improvements: production time was reduced by 25.37% and 22.37% in the two cases, respectively. Total energy consumption was decreased by 22.57% and 9.10%. Equipment idle time was reduced by 32.65% and 25.99%. Furthermore, the algorithm performs robustly in real-world, high-efficiency pipeline production scheduling environments. It outperforms other mainstream optimization algorithms across key metrics, including production time, energy consumption, idle time, and cost. The findings highlight the substantial advantages of the proposed algorithm for optimizing mechanical manufacturing production scheduling. By improving production efficiency, reducing energy consumption, and minimizing costs, this method offers a promising solution for intelligent optimization in the manufacturing sector. © 2025 The Author(s).},
	type = {Article},
	publication_stage = {Final},
	source = {Scopus},
	note = {Cited by: 0; All Open Access; Bronze Open Access}
